Marchionne: No reprieve for Chrysler factories DETROIT — Chrysler Group still plans to shutter eight North American plants according to its initial schedule, CEO Sergio Marchionne said, dismissing recent reports that the Sterling Heights, Mich., plant would get a reprieve.
Marchionne, who also heads Italian carmaker Fiat S.p.A., said Chrysler will stay with decisions it made at the time of its April 30 bankruptcy filing, He said, “There are no plans on my desk that the decision is going to be reversed.” — Reuters Prius will get sibling hybrid sedan in Japan TOKYO — The Toyota brand is getting its first dedicated hybrid sedan, a sibling to the Lexus HS 250h that will sport a more powerful engine than the Prius hatchback. On Oct. 20, the Toyota Sai will go on sale in Japan. It will be the second hybrid-only Toyota, after the Prius. Toyota did not say whether the Sai will be offered in the United States. — Hans Greimel Chevy Volt engineer Bob Kruse leaves GM DETROIT — Bob Kruse, one of the key architects of General Motors Co.’s highly touted Chevrolet Volt program, has quit to start a consulting firm that will help automakers and suppliers with engineering for hybrid and electric vehicles. GM named Micky Bly to replace Kruse as GM’s executive director of vehicle engineering for hybrids, electric vehicles and batteries. The Volt is scheduled to debut late next year. — Richard Truett Copyright 2009 Crain Communications Inc. All Rights Reserved.
